legendContents.description: Lower Density Growth Management Areas are areas designated in the Zoning Resolution where new developments must provide more off-street parking, larger yards and more open space than would otherwise be required in the applicable zoning districts In Staten Island and Bronx Community District 10.

Zoning Map Amendments include adopted & proposed changes in the zoning district of a property which allow different land uses (residential, commercial, industrial, etc.) and density (number of dwelling units or size of buildings) requirements on that property.

The Inclusionary Housing Designated Areas Program was created in 2005 to encourage the creation and preservation of affordable housing in medium and high-density neighborhoods being rezoned to create new housing opportunities. The program modifies the base floor area ratio (FAR) available for developments and offers a floor area bonus for developments that provide affordable housing either on-site or within the surrounding community.

A Sidewalk Cafe is a portion of an eating or drinking estab­lishment that is located on a public sidewalk including enclosed areas (within a structure) & unenclosed area (with removable tables etc.). Sidewalk cafe regulations are administered by the Department of Consumer Affairs.
NYC City Owned and Leased Properties (COLP)
Commercial District Overlays are C1 or C2 district mapped within residential districts to serve local retail needs such as grocery stores, dry cleaners or restaurants.
City parks, playgrounds & public green spaces.

A Business Improvement District (BID) is a public/private partnership in which property and business owners elect to make a collective contribution to the maintenance, development, and promotion of their commercial district.
Limited Height Districts are zoning areas with building height restrictions of 50 - 100 ft that may be superimposed on areas designated as historic districts by the Landmarks Preservation Commission.

The Coastal Zone Boundary defines the geographic scope of New York City's Waterfront Revitalization Program (WRP). The boundary encompasses all land and water of direct and significant impact on coastal waters.

The New York City Waterfront Revitalization Program (WRP) is the city's principal coastal zone management tool. It establishes the City's policies for development and use of the waterfront. Most City, State and Federal discretionary actions in the Coastal Zone must be reviewed for consistency with these policies.

Hurricane Evacuation Zones are areas of the city that may be inundated by storm surge or isolated by storm surge waters. The six zones are ranked by the risk of storm surge impact, with Zone 1 being the most likely to flood.

Neighborhood Tabulation Areas (NTAs) were created to project populations at a small area level, from 2000 to 2030 for PlaNYC, the long-term sustainability plan for New York City.
The 2010 NYC Public Use Microdata Areas (PUMAs) are statistical geographic areas defined for the dissemination of Public Use Microdata Sample (PUMS) data.

parameters.param1: 'NY Data: Waterfront Access Plan Zoning Overlay'

legendContents.description: A waterfront access plan is a detailed framework set forth in the Zoning Resolution, that tailors waterfront bulk regulations and public access requirements to the specific conditions of a particular waterfront. Development of individual waterfront parcels governed by the plan trig­gers a requirement to build and maintain public access areas in accordance with the WAP.

A waterfront area is the geographical area adjacent to a body of water at least 100 feet wide, comprising all blocks between the pierhead line and a parallel line 800 feet landward from the shoreline. Blocks within the waterfront area are subject to waterfront zoning regulations.

Businesses that qualify and operate in one of two New York City Empowerment Zones (South Bronx or Upper Manhattan) may be eligible for an employer wage credit for increased depreciation tax deductions.
A FRESH food store is a full-line grocery store, established in underserved neighborhoods through zoning incentives, that promotes the sale of fresh food products.

Transit Zones are areas where special parking provisions apply. The boundaries are mapped to encompass neighborhoods that are dense, proximate to public transportation options, and where car ownership rates are lowest.
